\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {8}{\ignorespaces \textit  {The Temptation of Christ} by \textbf  {Ary Scheffer} (1795-1858) is a dramatic painting from 1854 presenting one of the most psychologically intense moments in the New Testament --- the Devil's final temptation of Jesus in the wilderness (\textbf  {Mathew 4:8-10}) (Says Telegram channel \url  {https://t.me/aetatesolis/4601} that among other things is renown for treating of topics such as history, art, and yes, Europeanism). Moreover, and worth noting concerning this classic painting; one can observe that, just like the suggestion Daniel Defoe left in his 18th century tale of Robison Crusoe (see \textbf  {\hyperref  [SEC41]{Section \ref {SEC41}}}); \textbf  {that in his most cunning forms, Satan appears in human form}; is indeed a powerfully influential idea, and could likely have inspired later art such we see depicted here in Scheffer's painting.}}{62}{figure.caption.12}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{FIGCHRST}{{8}{62}{\textit {The Temptation of Christ} by \textbf {Ary Scheffer} (1795-1858) is a dramatic painting from 1854 presenting one of the most psychologically intense moments in the New Testament --- the Devil's final temptation of Jesus in the wilderness (\textbf {Mathew 4:8-10}) (Says Telegram channel \url {https://t.me/aetatesolis/4601} that among other things is renown for treating of topics such as history, art, and yes, Europeanism). Moreover, and worth noting concerning this classic painting; one can observe that, just like the suggestion Daniel Defoe left in his 18th century tale of Robison Crusoe (see \textbf {\hyperref [SEC41]{Section \ref {SEC41}}}); \textbf {that in his most cunning forms, Satan appears in human form}; is indeed a powerfully influential idea, and could likely have inspired later art such we see depicted here in Scheffer's painting}{figure.caption.12}{}}
